  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that TypeScript type design should aim for interfaces that are both **consistent** and **predictable**, avoiding the trade‑off between a monolithic “big picture” type and a proliferation of tiny named types. It introduces three “guerrilla” techniques: (1) **Why not all** – define a single large primary interface and then extract sub‑types via indexed access (`ProductDetails[\"seller\"]`, etc.) to keep documentation in one place without duplication; (2) **Mix‑ins** – compose reusable field groups into logical objects, leveraging TypeScript’s intersection types and utility types; and (3) **Namespaces** – organize related types under a namespace to improve discoverability and IDE tooling. The tone is a hands‑on tutorial with a playful, “guerrilla” metaphor, targeting TypeScript developers who work with semi‑structured API data and want pragmatic, DRY‑friendly patterns beyond traditional OOP or ER‑diagram approaches.",
